-- BG Group, Chemring, Halma, HSBC, Whitbread: U.K., Irish Equity Preview
-- Adria Cimino
-- 2010-06-22T06:39:37Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-21/chemring-halma-hsbc-holdings-plc-whitbread-u-k-irish-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following is a list of companies
whose shares may have unusual price changes in U.K. and Irish
markets. Stock symbols are in parentheses and prices are from
the last market close.  
 The benchmark  FTSE 100 Index  rose 48.27, or 0.9 percent, to
5,299.11. The  FTSE All-Share Index  climbed 0.8 percent and
Ireland’s  ISEQ Index  advanced less than 0.1 percent.  
 BG Group Plc  (BG/ LN): The U.K.’s third-largest natural-gas
producer was downgraded to “neutral” from “buy” at Goldman
Sachs Group Inc. after recent share-price gains. The stock
increased 0.8 percent to 1,125 pence.  
 BP Plc  (BP/ LN): The oil company aims to sell assets,
improve its safety standards and may replace Chief Executive
Officer  Tony Hayward  as part of a three-stage recovery plan
after shares plummeted in the wake of the Gulf of Mexico oil
spill, Handelsblatt reported, without saying how it obtained the
information. The stock slid 2.2 percent to 349.5 pence.  
 Bunzl Plc  (BNZL LN): The biggest U.K. supplier of vending
machines said trading in the six months through June was in line
with full-year expectations, with revenue growth of 2 percent.
The stock rose 0.2 percent to 746.5 pence.  
 Chemring Group Plc  (CHG LN): The developer of missile-
avoidance gear for the U.S.’s Joint Strike Fighter reported
first-half revenue of 255.9 million pounds ($377 million), in
line with analyst estimates. The shares fell 1.6 percent to
3,310 pence.  
 EasyJet Plc  (EZJ LN) and  Ryanair Holdings Plc  (RYA ID): The
airlines were both cut to “neutral” from “overweight” at
JPMorgan Chase & Co. EasyJet slipped 0.1 percent to 426.5 pence.
Ryanair lost 2.9 percent to 3.66 euros.  
 Halma Plc  (HLMA LN): The world’s second-biggest maker of
smoke detectors said full-year net income rose to 60.43 million
pounds. The stock rose 2 percent to 271 pence.  
 HSBC Holdings Plc  (HSBA LN): The bank’s Russia Chief
Executive Officer  Stuart Lawson  has left the company and his
deputy,  Rob Carver , was appointed interim CEO, according to a
person with direct knowledge who cited an internal memo. The
shares climbed 1.7 percent to 659.3 pence.  
 Michael Page International Plc  (MPI LN): UBS AG raised its
recommendation on shares of the U.K.’s second-largest
recruitment company to “buy” from “neutral.” The stock
gained 0.6 percent to 402.6 pence.  
 Whitbread Plc  (WTB LN): The operator of Premier Inn budget
hotels said sales at outlets open at least a year rose 7.6
percent in the 13 weeks ended June 3. The stock advanced less
than 0.1 percent to 1,478 pence.  
